Edit `platform/plugin-sdk/src/storage.ts`, function `getLocalStorage` at lines 11-17.

Current implementation:
```typescript
export const getLocalStorage = (key: string): string | null => {
  try {
    return localStorage.getItem(key);
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
};
```

The problem: when `window.localStorage` is undefined (not just throws on access), `localStorage.getItem(key)` throws a ReferenceError or TypeError. The catch block returns null, but we could try an iframe fallback before giving up.

New implementation pattern:
```typescript
export const getLocalStorage = (key: string): string | null => {
  // Fast path: direct access
  try {
    if (typeof localStorage !== 'undefined') {
      return localStorage.getItem(key);
    }
  } catch {
    // Fall through to iframe fallback
  }

  // Iframe fallback: some apps (e.g., Discord) delete window.localStorage
  // but same-origin iframes retain access to the underlying storage
  try {
    const iframe = document.createElement('iframe');
    iframe.style.display = 'none';
    document.body.appendChild(iframe);
    try {
      const storage = iframe.contentWindow?.localStorage;
      return storage ? storage.getItem(key) : null;
    } finally {
      document.body.removeChild(iframe);
    }
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
};
```

IMPORTANT: The SDK runs in browser page context only. `document` and `window` are available. This code needs to work in the browser, not in Node.js.

Also consider if setLocalStorage and removeLocalStorage need similar treatment. For setLocalStorage, the fallback should also try the iframe approach. For removeLocalStorage, same pattern.

Make sure to NOT break the existing behavior — the function must still return null when localStorage is truly inaccessible (e.g., in sandboxed iframes where even the iframe approach won't work).
